226→\section{System architecture}
227→\label{sec:architecture}
228→
229→This section presents the architecture of the proposed multi-strategy GraphRAG system. We begin with formal notation and the financial domain ontology (Section~\ref{sec:notation}), then describe the ingestion pipeline (Section~\ref{sec:ingestion}), the multi-strategy retrieval engine (Section~\ref{sec:retrieval}), and the security model (Section~\ref{sec:security}). Figure~\ref{fig:architecture} provides an overview of the complete system.
230→
231→\subsection{Formal notation and ontology}
232→\label{sec:notation}
233→
234→\textbf{Document corpus.} Let $\mathcal{D} = \{d_1, \ldots, d_M\}$ denote a collection of financial documents including regulatory frameworks, SEC filings, and audit reports.
235→
236→\textbf{Knowledge graph.} We define the knowledge graph as $G = (V, E, \varphi, \psi)$ where:
237→\begin{itemize}
238→    \item $V$ is the set of entities (nodes),
239→    \item $E \subseteq V \times V$ is the set of relationships (edges),
240→    \item $\varphi: V \rightarrow \mathcal{T}_V$ maps entities to entity types,
241→    \item $\psi: E \rightarrow \mathcal{T}_E$ maps edges to relationship types.
242→\end{itemize}
243→
244→\textbf{Entity types.} The financial domain ontology defines 10 entity types:
245→\begin{equation}
246→\mathcal{T}_V = \{\textsc{Regulation}, \textsc{Article}, \textsc{Requirement}, \textsc{RiskCategory}, \textsc{FinancialMetric}, \textsc{Company}, \textsc{Subsidiary}, \textsc{Jurisdiction}, \textsc{Control}, \textsc{AuditFinding}\}
247→\end{equation}
248→
249→\textbf{Relationship types.} The ontology defines 14 relationship types:
250→\begin{equation}
251→\begin{split}
252→\mathcal{T}_E = \{&\textsc{Regulates}, \textsc{Requires}, \textsc{Defines}, \textsc{ExposesTo}, \textsc{SubsidiaryOf}, \\
253→&\textsc{OperatesIn}, \textsc{AuditedBy}, \textsc{Mitigates}, \textsc{References}, \\
254→&\textsc{Supersedes}, \textsc{ComposedOf}, \textsc{ReportsTo}, \textsc{ValidatedBy}, \textsc{CompliesWith}\}
255→\end{split}
256→\end{equation}
257→
258→Table~\ref{tab:ontology} provides the complete ontology specification with entity types, descriptions, and examples.
259→
260→\begin{table}[t]
261→\caption{Financial domain ontology: entity types with descriptions and examples from the evaluation corpus.}
262→\label{tab:ontology}
263→\centering
264→\small
265→\begin{tabular}{@{}llp{5cm}@{}}
266→\toprule
267→\textbf{Entity Type} & \textbf{Count} & \textbf{Examples} \\
268→\midrule
269→Regulation & 15 & Basel III, LGPD, GDPR, SOX \\
270→Article & 120 & LGPD Art. 18, GDPR Art. 25 \\
271→Requirement & 85 & Capital adequacy ratio, Data minimization \\
272→RiskCategory & 12 & Credit risk, Operational risk, Market risk \\
273→FinancialMetric & 45 & Revenue, Net income, Basel ratio \\
274→Company & 50 & S\&P 100 companies \\
275→Subsidiary & 80 & Corporate subsidiaries from 10-K filings \\
276→Jurisdiction & 20 & Brazil, EU, United States \\
277→Control & 100 & Internal controls from audit reports \\
278→AuditFinding & 200 & Simulated audit findings with risk ratings \\
279→\bottomrule
280→\end{tabular}
281→\end{table}
282→
283→\textbf{Triple.} A triple $t = (s, p, o) \in V \times \mathcal{T}_E \times V$ represents a relationship, with an associated confidence score $c(t) \in [0, 1]$ assigned during extraction.
284→
285→\textbf{Chunks.} The document corpus is segmented into chunks $\mathcal{C} = \{c_1, \ldots, c_K\}$, where each chunk $c_k$ has:
286→\begin{itemize}
287→    \item Type: $\tau(c_k) \in \{\textsc{PythonClass}, \textsc{PythonFunction}, \textsc{MarkdownSection}, \textsc{NotebookCellGroup}\}$,
288→    \item Embedding: $\mathbf{e}(c_k) \in \mathbb{R}^d$ with $d = 384$ (all-MiniLM-L6-v2),
289→    \item Content hash: $h(c_k) = \text{SHA-256}(\text{content}(c_k))$ for incremental processing.
290→\end{itemize}
291→
292→\textbf{Communities.} A community partition $\Gamma = \{\gamma_1, \ldots, \gamma_L\}$ of $G$ is computed via the Leiden algorithm \citep{traag2019leiden} with resolution parameter $r$. Each community $\gamma_l$ has a textual summary $\text{summary}(\gamma_l)$ generated by the LLM and an embedding $\mathbf{e}(\text{summary}(\gamma_l)) \in \mathbb{R}^d$.
293→
294→\textbf{Query model.} A query $q$ has an associated intent $\iota(q) \in \mathcal{I}$ where:
295→\begin{equation}
296→\mathcal{I} = \{\textsc{Validation}, \textsc{Comparison}, \textsc{Recommendation}, \textsc{Explanation}, \textsc{CodeExample}, \textsc{General}\}
297→\end{equation}
298→
299→\textbf{Security context.} Each query carries a security context $\sigma = (\text{user\_id}, \text{role}, \text{permissions}, \text{tenant\_id})$ that constrains retrieval and generation.
300→
301→\subsection{Ingestion pipeline}
302→\label{sec:ingestion}
303→
304→The ingestion pipeline transforms raw financial documents into a knowledge graph through four stages: chunking, triple extraction, entity resolution, and graph loading, followed by community detection. Algorithm~\ref{alg:ingestion} provides the pseudocode.
305→
306→\begin{algorithm}[t]
307→\caption{Ingestion Pipeline}
308→\label{alg:ingestion}
309→\begin{algorithmic}[1]
310→\Require Document corpus $\mathcal{D}$, ontology $(\mathcal{T}_V, \mathcal{T}_E)$, alias dictionary $\mathcal{A}$, fuzzy threshold $\theta = 0.85$
311→\Ensure Knowledge graph $G = (V, E, \varphi, \psi)$, communities $\Gamma$
312→\State $\mathcal{C} \gets \emptyset$ \Comment{Chunk collection}
313→\For{each document $d \in \mathcal{D}$}
314→    \State $h_{\text{new}} \gets \text{SHA-256}(\text{content}(d))$
315→    \If{$h_{\text{new}} \neq h_{\text{cache}}(d)$}
316→        \State $\text{parser} \gets \text{SelectParser}(\text{type}(d))$ \Comment{Python/Markdown/Notebook}
317→        \State $\mathcal{C} \gets \mathcal{C} \cup \text{parser.chunk}(d)$
318→        \State $h_{\text{cache}}(d) \gets h_{\text{new}}$
319→    \Else
320→        \State $\mathcal{C} \gets \mathcal{C} \cup \text{LoadFromCache}(d)$
321→    \EndIf
322→\EndFor
323→\State $\mathcal{T}_{\text{raw}} \gets \emptyset$ \Comment{Raw triples}
324→\For{each chunk $c_k \in \mathcal{C}$} \Comment{Via Batch API for 50\% savings}
325→    \State $\mathcal{T}_{\text{raw}} \gets \mathcal{T}_{\text{raw}} \cup \text{LLM-Extract}(c_k, \mathcal{T}_V, \mathcal{T}_E)$
326→\EndFor
327→\State $\mathcal{T}_{\text{resolved}} \gets \emptyset$ \Comment{Resolved triples}
328→\For{each triple $(s, p, o) \in \mathcal{T}_{\text{raw}}$}
329→    \State $s' \gets \text{Resolve}(s, \mathcal{A}, \theta)$ \Comment{Exact $\to$ case-insensitive $\to$ fuzzy}
330→    \State $o' \gets \text{Resolve}(o, \mathcal{A}, \theta)$
331→    \If{$\varphi(s') \in \mathcal{T}_V$ \textbf{and} $\varphi(o') \in \mathcal{T}_E$}
332→        \State $\mathcal{T}_{\text{resolved}} \gets \mathcal{T}_{\text{resolved}} \cup \{(s', p, o')\}$
333→    \EndIf
334→\EndFor
335→\State $G \gets \text{LoadGraph}(\mathcal{T}_{\text{resolved}})$ \Comment{Cypher MERGE with uniqueness constraints}
336→\State $\Gamma \gets \text{Leiden}(G, r=1.0)$ \Comment{Community detection}
337→\For{each $\gamma_l \in \Gamma$}
338→    \State $\text{summary}(\gamma_l) \gets \text{LLM-Summarize}(\gamma_l)$
339→    \State $\mathbf{e}(\text{summary}(\gamma_l)) \gets \text{Embed}(\text{summary}(\gamma_l))$
340→\EndFor
341→\State \Return $G, \Gamma$
342→\end{algorithmic}
343→\end{algorithm}
344→
345→\textbf{Stage 1: Chunking.} The chunker dispatches documents to specialized parsers based on file type. The Python parser uses AST analysis to extract class and function boundaries, preserving semantic coherence. The Markdown parser segments by H2/H3 headers, maintaining the hierarchical structure of regulatory documents. The Notebook parser groups related cells. All parsers compute content hashes for incremental processing: only documents whose hash differs from the cached value are reprocessed, which is critical when the corpus contains thousands of regulatory filings.
346→
347→\textbf{Stage 2: Triple extraction.} Each chunk is processed via the LLM API with an ontology-constrained prompt that specifies valid entity types $\mathcal{T}_V$ and relationship types $\mathcal{T}_E$. The prompt instructs the model to extract triples in the form $(s, p, o)$ with confidence scores $c(t) \in [0, 1]$ and textual evidence from the source. For batch processing of more than 50 chunks, we use the Batch API, which provides a 50\% discount on API costs:
348→\begin{equation}
349→T_{\text{batch}} = 0.5 \times \sum_{k=1}^{K} (T_{\text{system}} + T_{\text{fewshot}} + T_{\text{chunk}_k} + T_{\text{output}_k})
350→\end{equation}
351→
352→\textbf{Stage 3: Entity resolution.} Entities are resolved through three levels: (1)~exact match against the alias dictionary ($\sim$130 aliases), (2)~case-insensitive normalization, and (3)~fuzzy matching via sequence similarity with threshold $\theta = 0.85$. Resolved entities are validated against the ontology; entities with invalid types are discarded. For duplicate triples $(s, p, o)$, the instance with the highest confidence $c(t)$ is retained.
353→
354→\textbf{Stage 4: Graph loading.} Resolved triples are loaded into Neo4j using Cypher MERGE operations with 10 uniqueness constraints (one per entity type) and full-text indices for entity search.
355→
356→\textbf{Stage 5: Community detection.} The Leiden algorithm \citep{traag2019leiden} partitions the graph into communities with guaranteed well-connectedness---a property the Louvain algorithm cannot guarantee and which is critical for financial graphs where regulatory entities must be correctly grouped. Each community receives an LLM-generated textual summary and corresponding embedding.
357→
358→\subsection{Multi-strategy retrieval}
359→\label{sec:retrieval}
360→
361→The central algorithmic contribution of this work is the multi-strategy retrieval engine that executes three retrieval strategies in parallel and fuses their results using intent-aware weighting. Algorithm~\ref{alg:retrieval} provides the pseudocode, and Figure~\ref{fig:retrieval} illustrates the pipeline.
362→
363→\begin{algorithm}[t]
364→\caption{Multi-Strategy Intent-Aware Retrieval}
365→\label{alg:retrieval}
366→\begin{algorithmic}[1]
367→\Require Query $q$, security context $\sigma$, knowledge graph $G$, communities $\Gamma$, weight table $\mathbf{W}$, token budget $B$
368→\Ensure Ranked context $\mathcal{R}$, intent $\iota$
369→\State \textbf{// Authentication and Authorization}
370→\State \text{Verify}($\sigma$) \Comment{JWT validation, RBAC check}
371→\State $G_\sigma \gets \text{TenantFilter}(G, \sigma.\text{tenant\_id})$ \Comment{Restrict to tenant subgraph}
372→\State \textbf{// Intent Classification}
373→\State $\iota \gets \text{ClassifyIntent}(q)$ \Comment{Pattern matching for 6 intent types}
374→\State $\mathcal{E}_q \gets \text{ExtractEntities}(q, \mathcal{A})$ \Comment{Longest-match-first}
375→\State $(w_g, w_v, w_c) \gets \mathbf{W}[\iota]$ \Comment{Intent-specific weights}
376→\State \textbf{// Parallel Retrieval}
377→\State $\mathcal{R}_g \gets \text{GraphRetriever}(G_\sigma, \mathcal{E}_q, \iota)$ \textbf{in parallel}
378→\State $\mathcal{R}_v \gets \text{VectorRetriever}(q, G_\sigma, \iota)$ \textbf{in parallel}
379→\State $\mathcal{R}_c \gets \text{CommunityRetriever}(q, \mathcal{E}_q, \Gamma)$ \textbf{in parallel}
380→\State \textbf{// Fusion and Ranking}
381→\For{each result $r \in \mathcal{R}_g \cup \mathcal{R}_v \cup \mathcal{R}_c$}
382→    \State $\text{score}(r) \gets w_g \cdot \hat{s}_g(r) + w_v \cdot \hat{s}_v(r) + w_c \cdot \hat{s}_c(r)$
383→    \Comment{$\hat{s}$: min-max normalized scores}
384→\EndFor
385→\State $\mathcal{R} \gets \text{Deduplicate}(\mathcal{R}_g \cup \mathcal{R}_v \cup \mathcal{R}_c)$ \Comment{Keep highest score per chunk}
386→\State $\mathcal{R} \gets \text{SortDescending}(\mathcal{R}, \text{score})$
387→\State $\mathcal{R} \gets \text{TruncateByBudget}(\mathcal{R}, B, \text{min\_results}=3)$
388→\State $\mathcal{R} \gets \text{PermissionFilter}(\mathcal{R}, \sigma)$ \Comment{Post-retrieval security check}
389→\State \Return $\mathcal{R}, \iota$
390→\end{algorithmic}
391→\end{algorithm}
392→
393→\subsubsection{Intent parser}
394→\label{sec:intent-parser}
395→
396→The intent parser classifies each query into one of six intent types using pattern matching against bilingual (Portuguese and English) keyword dictionaries. Each intent type is associated with a weight vector that determines the relative contribution of each retrieval strategy. Table~\ref{tab:weights} presents the weight configuration.
397→
398→\begin{table}[t]
399→\caption{Intent-aware retrieval weights. Each row specifies the relative contribution of graph, vector, and community retrieval strategies for a given query intent type.}
400→\label{tab:weights}
401→\centering
402→\begin{tabular}{@{}llccc@{}}
403→\toprule
404→\textbf{Intent} & \textbf{Typical patterns} & $w_g$ & $w_v$ & $w_c$ \\
405→\midrule
406→\textsc{Validation} & validate, check, verify & 0.7 & 0.2 & 0.1 \\
407→\textsc{Comparison} & compare, versus, between & 0.5 & 0.3 & 0.2 \\
408→\textsc{Recommendation} & best for, which model & 0.3 & 0.4 & 0.3 \\
409→\textsc{Explanation} & explain, how does, what is & 0.4 & 0.4 & 0.2 \\
410→\textsc{CodeExample} & code, example, how to use & 0.3 & 0.6 & 0.1 \\
411→\textsc{General} & (default) & 0.3 & 0.3 & 0.4 \\
412→\bottomrule
413→\end{tabular}
414→\end{table}
415→
416→The rationale for these weights reflects the information needs of each intent type. Validation queries benefit most from graph traversal because they require verifying specific relationships between entities (e.g., ``Does Article 18 of LGPD apply to credit data?''). Code example queries favor vector retrieval because they benefit from semantic similarity to code snippets. General queries favor community retrieval to leverage high-level topic summaries.
417→
418→\subsubsection{Graph retriever}
419→\label{sec:graph-retriever}
420→
421→The graph retriever performs N-hop traversal from identified entities using Cypher queries adapted to the detected intent. For each entity $e \in \mathcal{E}_q$, the retriever executes a depth-limited traversal with $\text{max\_depth} = 2$ and computes a distance-decay score:
422→\begin{equation}
423→\text{score}_g(v) = 1.0 - \frac{\text{hop\_distance}(v)}{2 \cdot \text{max\_depth}}
424→\label{eq:graph-score}
425→\end{equation}
426→This yields scores in the range $[0.5, 1.0]$, with closer nodes receiving higher scores. Intent-specific traversal patterns prioritize different relationship types: validation queries follow \textsc{Validates} and \textsc{CompliesWith} edges, while comparison queries perform multi-entity traversals to find common and differentiating attributes.
427→
428→\subsubsection{Vector retriever}
429→\label{sec:vector-retriever}
430→
431→The vector retriever computes the embedding $\mathbf{e}(q)$ of the query using sentence-transformers (all-MiniLM-L6-v2, $d=384$) and searches the Neo4j vector index for chunks with cosine similarity above a minimum threshold of 0.5. Results are filtered by chunk type based on the detected intent (e.g., code example queries prioritize \textsc{PythonFunction} chunks). Each retrieved chunk is enriched with its graph neighborhood to provide relational context.
432→
433→\subsubsection{Community retriever}
434→\label{sec:community-retriever}
435→
436→The community retriever employs a dual approach: (1)~entity membership lookup, returning the community of each identified entity with score 1.0, and (2)~summary similarity, computing cosine similarity between the query embedding and community summary embeddings. This combination ensures both direct entity matches and topically relevant communities are retrieved.
437→
438→\subsubsection{Context ranking and fusion}
439→\label{sec:context-ranker}
440→
441→Results from all three strategies are fused using a weighted score:
442→\begin{equation}
443→\text{score}_{\text{final}}(r) = \sum_{s \in \{g, v, c\}} w_s(\iota) \cdot \hat{s}_s(r)
444→\label{eq:fusion}
445→\end{equation}
446→where $w_s(\iota)$ is the weight for strategy $s$ given intent $\iota$ (from Table~\ref{tab:weights}), and $\hat{s}_s(r) \in [0, 1]$ is the min-max normalized score within each strategy. For results appearing in multiple strategies, the maximum score is retained. The ranked results are truncated to fit the token budget $B$ (default: 4,000 tokens), maintaining a minimum of 3 results regardless of budget constraints.
447→
